	  <abstract> 

<t>This short document outlines requirements for DTN key management. It may or may not
grow to specify some DTN key management schemes. </t> 


      </abstract>
   </front>
   <middle>

<section title="Introduction" toc="default">

<t>The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT",
"SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this document
are to be interpreted as described in <xref target="refs.RFC2119"
format="default" pageno="false"/>.</t>

<t>This document lists a set of putative requirements for key managment
for DTN protocols, in particular the bundle  protocol <xref
target="refs.DTNBP" format="default" pageno="false"/> 
with the aim of assisting in the development of workable key mangement 
schemes for 
the bundle security protocol
<xref target="refs.DTNBPsec" format="default" pageno="false"/>.  </t> 

<t>Readers should also consult the DTN Architecure RFC <xref target="RFC4838" format="default" pageno="false"/> 
and the DTN Security Overview and Motivations document <xref
target="refs.DTNsecOver" format="default" pageno="false"/> which contains an overview
of the current work on DTN security.</t> 

<t>Depending on what happens, this document might grow to include the specification
of some key management schemes.</t>
</section>

<section title="Key Management Requirements">

<list style="numbers">

<t>No single KM scheme will work for all DTNs therefore a set of schemes, or a framework, is REQUIRED.</t>

<t>All schemes MUST support some well-defined BSP ciphersuite(s).</t>

<t>At least one scheme SHOULD be defined for each of:</t>

<list style="numbers">
<t>Manual keying, i.e. pre-shared secrets or pre-installed public keys; </t>
<t>Key transport & key agreement options. </t>
</list>

<t>Schemes SHOULD be able to use extension blocks to piggy-back KM information
with application-data handling bundles.</t>

<t>Schemes MAY involve use of specific bundle payloads.</t>

<t>Some schemes MUST be defined using standard, well-known techniques (e.g. RSA key transport).</t>

<t>DTN node connectivity, computation and storage capabilities vary enormously, so some
scheme for highly challenged nodes SHOULD be defined.</t>

</list>

</section>

<section title="Security Considerations">

<t>This memo is entirely about security requirements. See above.</t>

</section>


<section title="IANA Considerations">

<t>For now, there are none. If specific DTN key managmenet schemes are defined
that meet these requirements, then an IANA registry, or entries in an IANA
registry, MAY be required.</t>
</section>


